    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "> To be sure I need a way to see Figma in dark theme.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, not all screen designs are done in dark theme. But they use the colors defined in the color palette here, in which you can map each color to its dark theme equivalent: https://www.figma.com/file/eghXX5JkzSM14Wtgyx1S2u/%F0%9F%8E%A8-Design-System-%E2%8E%9C-Desktop-Backup?node-id=1%3A10\r\n\r\nBecause colors don't always match exactly in both themes (for example what's 10% blue in light mode might be 20% blue in dark mode), we have a naming system that doesn't use concrete color names.\r\n\r\nSee below:\r\n\r\n![Screenshot from 2022-05-06 07-43-33](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/445106/167073992-2dff1c1d-e51c-422a-8027-2aa4db1e48f5.png)\r\n\r\nNotice the names (Primary, Base, Danger, Success, ... etc) and the number matrix. If you're looking for 10% light blue in light mode, you can see that it's the color located at \"Primary:3\" in light mode, which maps to `Theme.palette.primaryColor3` in QML.\r\n\r\nAlso, notice how \"Primary:3\" is **not** 10% light blue, but 20% light blue. \r\nOur color palette system in QML takes this already into account.\r\n\r\nBottom line: You don't need to introduce new colors, they already exist here: https://github.com/status-im/StatusQ/blob/master/src/StatusQ/Core/Theme/ThemePalette.qml#L40-L91\r\n\r\nAnd they are specifically defined for individual themes here: \r\n\r\n- https://github.com/status-im/StatusQ/blob/master/src/StatusQ/Core/Theme/StatusLightTheme.qml#L101-L146\r\n- https://github.com/status-im/StatusQ/blob/master/src/StatusQ/Core/Theme/StatusDarkTheme.qml#L97-L148\r\n\r\nFor more info on the reasoning of everything, checkout: https://github.com/status-im/StatusQ/issues/3",
